{
  "texts": [
    "In responding to this worry, Davidsonians have two options: they can treat putative actions mediated by BCIs as subject to a version of the bodily constraint that treats the substrate of an intention 's BCI-mediated proximate effect as the agent's'body' or they can put BCI actions in a separate category (in something like the same way as they might exclude internal cognitive actions; see §3.3).",
    "Assuming the latter strategy can be defended, BCI-mediated actions pose no problems for the standard story because they fall outside of its domain of applicability.",
    "But even on the first strategy, the Davidsonian argument of this section follows, allowing for a modified version of the strict bodily constraint derived from this BCI-accommodating modification to the liberal constraint.",
    "Though in this case 1 3 say that these movements are parts of a larger whole action that includes changes in the wider environment.",
    "But in this case, the action would be non-identical to (because differing in causal profile with) an agent's basic actions."
  ]
}